ship written on The Monk's Tale and the Nun's Priest's Tale in the twentieth century with a view to revisiting the former and creating a comprehensive scholarly view of the latter. A detailed introduction summarizes all extant writings on the two tales and their relationship to each other, giving a sense of the complexity of Chaucer's seminal work and the unique function of its component stories. By dealing with these two tales in particular, this bibliography suggests the complicated critical reception and history of The Canterbury Tales.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442687608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442687608.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG